👉 ARRAYS IN JAVA

👉 Definition:

Array is a collection of similar types of data stored in contiguous memory locations.
All elements in an array must be of the same data type.

👉 Use Case:
Arrays are used when we want to store multiple values of the same type using a single variable name.
Example: Storing marks of 5 students.

👉 Instead of writing:
int m1 = 85;
int m2 = 90;
int m3 = 78;
int m4 = 88;
int m5 = 92;

👉 We use an array:
int[] marks = new int[5];

👉 Syntax:
datatype[] arrayName = new datatype[size];

OR

👉 datatype arrayName[] = new datatype[size];

Example:
int[] marks = new int[5];

Indexing:
Array index starts from 0.
Last index = size - 1.

For an array of size 5:
Indexes are 0, 1, 2, 3, 4.

Assigning Values:
marks[0] = 85;
marks[1] = 90;
marks[2] = 78;
marks[3] = 88;
marks[4] = 92;

👉 Printing Array Elements using loop:

for(int i = 0; i < 5; i++)
{
System.out.println(marks[i]);
}

👉 Direct Initialization:
int[] marks = {85, 90, 78, 88, 92};

👉 Important Points:

1. Arrays store homogeneous (same type) data.
2. Size must be defined at the time of creation.
3. Array index always starts from 0.
4. Array length can be accessed using arrayName.length
5. Example: marks.length

👉 Three Ways to create an array : 

1.  int[] marks;  --> declaration
    marks = new int[5]; --> memory allocation

2.  int [] marks = new int[5]; --> Declaration + Memory Allocation

3.  int [] marks = {100,45,27,46,89}; --> Declare + initialize

Arrays indices starts from 0 and goes till (n-1) where n is the size of the array
